1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,720
Welcome back, everyone, to Walmart
Academy's The Art of Feedback. I’m Jamie,

2
00:00:05,720 --> 00:00:11,593
alongside leadership expert Alex. In our
last episode, we talked all about the

3
00:00:11,593 --> 00:00:17,237
timing of feedback—catching those
real-time moments. Today, we are tackling

4
00:00:17,237 --> 00:00:23,263
the million-dollar question: How do we
actually say the words without it turning

5
00:00:23,263 --> 00:00:25,246
into a defensive argument?

6
00:00:25,918 --> 00:00:31,170
[sighs] It is the toughest part of the
job for so many leaders, Jamie. Because

7
00:00:31,170 --> 00:00:36,217
feedback can easily get clouded by raw
emotion, or misinterpretation. If we

8
00:00:36,217 --> 00:00:40,924
aren't careful, a well-intentioned
conversation can quickly go off the

9
00:00:40,924 --> 00:00:45,562
rails. That is exactly why leaders have
to use a structured approach.

10
00:00:46,051 --> 00:00:48,290
We... need a blueprint!

11
00:00:48,896 --> 00:00:53,733
[energetic] Exactly! And the absolute
best blueprint out there is the SBI

12
00:00:53,733 --> 00:00:58,705
feedback model. It is a simple, highly
effective framework designed to make

13
00:00:58,705 --> 00:01:03,810
feedback significantly clearer. It keeps
the conversation strictly focused on

14
00:01:03,810 --> 00:01:08,110
observable facts, rather than subjective
assumptions or emotions.

15
00:01:08,713 --> 00:01:12,220
[Enthusiastic] Which naturally dials down
the defensiveness, I imagine?

16
00:01:12,847 --> 00:01:17,511
Dramatically. [emphatic] By relying on
this strict structure, you reduce

17
00:01:17,511 --> 00:01:21,978
misinterpretation, drop the defensive
shields, and pave the way for a

18
00:01:21,978 --> 00:01:24,343
productive, growth-focused dialogue.

19
00:01:25,011 --> 00:01:29,246
Okay, [surprised] I'm sold. What does SBI
stand for?

20
00:01:29,905 --> 00:01:35,950
[thoughtful] It stands for Situation,
Behavior, and Impact. Let’s break them

21
00:01:35,950 --> 00:01:42,398
down. First up is the "S"—Situation. You
must define the exact "where" and "when"

22
00:01:42,398 --> 00:01:46,267
of the situation you are discussing. Be
specific.

23
00:01:46,984 --> 00:01:50,502
So, what would be an ineffective way to
do that?

24
00:01:51,178 --> 00:01:55,906
An ineffective start sounds like this:
[annoyed] "When dealing with customers,

25
00:01:55,906 --> 00:02:00,327
you always act…" It's too broad, and
words like "always" immediately make

26
00:02:00,327 --> 00:02:04,502
people defensive, because it feels like
an attack on their character.

27
00:02:05,003 --> 00:02:10,108
[Enthusiastic] That makes sense. So, how
do we fix it using the "Situation" step?

28
00:02:10,690 --> 00:02:15,299
You anchor it in time and space. An
effective example would be: [explaining]

29
00:02:15,299 --> 00:02:20,216
"In our team meeting on Tuesday…" You've
just established the factual setting. No

30
00:02:20,216 --> 00:02:22,736
one can argue with Tuesday's team
meeting.

31
00:02:23,287 --> 00:02:29,919
[happy] Perfect. Okay, so we have our
Situation. What is the "B"—Behavior?

32
00:02:30,632 --> 00:02:35,445
[Cheeky] This is where you must describe
the specific behavior that actually

33
00:02:35,445 --> 00:02:39,808
occurred. Again, just the observable
facts. What did you see or hear?

34
00:02:40,378 --> 00:02:45,865
So, avoiding things like [annoyed] "you
were being rude," which is an assumption,

35
00:02:45,865 --> 00:02:48,677
and instead saying what they actually
did?

36
00:02:49,217 --> 00:02:54,030
[energetic] Exactly! Examples of
observable behavior would be: crossing

37
00:02:54,030 --> 00:02:59,669
arms, interrupting others, returning late
from lunch, or walking by a spill and not

38
00:02:59,669 --> 00:03:04,826
taking action. You are simply stating the
action that took place within that

39
00:03:04,826 --> 00:03:06,133
specific situation.

40
00:03:06,632 --> 00:03:13,734
[clears throat] Alright, that brings us
to the final piece: the "I"—Impact.

41
00:03:14,386 --> 00:03:18,818
[emphatic] Yes. You have to clearly
explain the impact that the behavior had

42
00:03:18,818 --> 00:03:23,368
on you, the customer, or the business as
a whole. This is the "why it matters"

43
00:03:23,368 --> 00:03:24,845
part of the conversation.

44
00:03:25,346 --> 00:03:28,216
[curious] Can you give us an example of a
negative impact?

45
00:03:28,928 --> 00:03:33,525
[thoughtful] Sure. Let's say the behavior
was leaving equipment out. The impact

46
00:03:33,525 --> 00:03:38,005
statement would be: [serious] "When
ladders aren't secured, our customers are

47
00:03:38,005 --> 00:03:41,777
put at risk." You connect the action
directly to the consequence.

48
00:03:42,291 --> 00:03:47,969
And we talked last episode about how
important it is to reinforce positive

49
00:03:47,969 --> 00:03:51,158
behavior, too. How does SBI work for
that?

50
00:03:51,645 --> 00:03:56,032
[thoughtful] It works beautifully for
positive reinforcement! Let's say an

51
00:03:56,032 --> 00:04:00,780
associate was doing a great job listening
during a huddle. Your impact statement

52
00:04:00,780 --> 00:04:05,589
might be: "When you make space for others
to finish their thoughts, it helps them

53
00:04:05,589 --> 00:04:07,031
feel heard and valued.".

54
00:04:07,668 --> 00:04:13,194
[energetic] Situation, Behavior, Impact.
It takes the guesswork and the emotion

55
00:04:13,194 --> 00:04:15,249
entirely out of the equation.

56
00:04:15,916 --> 00:04:20,820
[chuckles] It does. It transforms a
stressful confrontation into a clear,

57
00:04:20,820 --> 00:04:26,268
factual, and supportive conversation. Oh,
and Jamie? One more thing before we go.

58
00:04:26,754 --> 00:04:30,103
[laughs nervously] Uh oh. I don't like
that tone.

59
00:04:30,704 --> 00:04:34,954
[excited] Next up, it's test time. I
highly hope you—and everyone

60
00:04:34,954 --> 00:04:37,411
listening—have been paying attention.

61
00:04:37,962 --> 00:04:44,371
Wait, a pop quiz?! [Cheeky] Is this going
on my permanent record? I thought we were

62
00:04:44,371 --> 00:04:44,996
friends!

63
00:04:45,685 --> 00:04:51,836
[Cheeky] Consider this your "S"—the
Situation. Next episode, we're testing

64
00:04:51,836 --> 00:04:53,353
your "B"—Behavior.

65
00:04:53,864 --> 00:04:59,742
[laughs nervously] And the "I" is going
to be the Impact on my ego. [chuckles]

66
00:04:59,742 --> 00:05:04,475
Alright, folks, grab your No. 2 pencils
and cram while you can.

